ce:section.ce:para:
In summary, this study presents the design of an N and S co-doped carbon dots (CDs) catalyst (HT-CDs-1) with exceptional oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) activity, exhibiting a half-wave potential (E

                        1/2
                     ) as high as 0.91 V, surpassing most metal-free catalysts and even the benchmark Pt/C catalyst. The Zn-Air battery assembled using HT-CDs-1 demonstrates an impressive charge/discharge cycle time of up to 108 h. Notably, the active site configuration of the N, S co-doped catalyst is elucidated as N/C-S-N through XPS and FT-IR characterization techniques, enabling enhanced electron occupancy in anti-bonding molecular orbitals and facilitating efficient charge transfer from the catalyst to reactants. Density functional theory calculations highlight the synergistic effect between nitrogen and sulfur atoms, wherein new active sites (C-S-N), formed by fringing thiophene S groups, graphite N atoms, and pentagonal defects significantly reduce energy barriers (0.6 eV) in ORR reactions thereby optimizing catalytic reactivity. This finding provides insights into the activity origin of N,S co-doped catalysts while shedding light on mechanistic studies for metal-free catalysts.
